00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:11.480
So this is the map of Africa.

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:16.340
It's got a diverse population,
all races and all religions.

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:18.290
Almost all of them.

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:22.100
And it's got six of the top
12 fastest growing economies

00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:24.380
in the world.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:25.940
And it's got half
a billion people

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:29.030
who are subscribers
to mobile services,

00:01:29.030 --> 00:01:31.940
and a quarter billion of
those who use smartphones.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:35.390
There are more than 2,100
languages in Africa,

00:01:35.390 --> 00:01:38.590
and those are grouped
into fives groups.

00:01:38.590 --> 00:01:42.725
As you can see here,
Afroasiatic and Saharan,

00:01:42.725 --> 00:01:46.600
Niger-Congo, Khoisan,
and Austronesian.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:50.000
And there are 54
countries in Africa.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.570
And Fulani, which is the
language that we speak,

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:54.770
and for which we created
the ADLaM alphabet,

00:01:54.770 --> 00:02:00.554
is spoken in 23 countries
of those 54 countries.

00:02:00.554 --> 00:02:02.970
And as you can see on the map
here, you can see up there--

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:04.570
you see it in the red--

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:08.620
that's the Niger-Congo subgroup.

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:13.940
And Fulani is up there
between Guinea and Mali.

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:15.370
Fulanis.

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:18.940
There are more than 50
million of them in Africa.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:21.565
And you can-- if we
go to the next slide--

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:28.500
so this is actually a map of
Western and Central Africa.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:30.645
From Senegal up
here where it says

00:02:30.645 --> 00:02:32.970
Futa Toro all the way to Sudan.

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:34.950
These are regions
where you can actually

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:37.020
find Fulanis in Africa.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:39.300
In almost all of the
countries of West Africa,

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:43.530
the 16 countries plus some
countries of Central Africa,

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:47.390
and then as far as Sudan,
around the Nile River.

00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:48.420
So you can find Fulanis.

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:57.600
They are called
Fulanis by the British

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:01.110
and they got that name
from the Hausa people.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.110
And the French people
refer to us as Peul,

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:06.840
and they got those
names by the first tribe

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:09.540
they encountered when they
arrived in Africa, the Wolof

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:10.500
people.

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:17.537
But we call ourselves Pullo if
it's one and Fulbhe, for many.

00:03:17.537 --> 00:03:18.620
And there are other names.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:20.730
The Arab people
use [? Fellata. ?]

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:26.340
And Fula is also at term
used by the Mandingoes.

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:28.050
And there are also
some other subgroups

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:30.970
within the group of Fulani
people, the Wodaabhe,

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:34.950
the Bororo, the Wassulu people,
and the Toucouleur in Senegal.

00:03:34.950 --> 00:03:36.900
And we are historically
nomadic people,

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:40.650
and that's explain why we
are spread all over Africa,

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:42.760
because we are cattle
herders, so we--

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:46.080
wherever we find green
pasture, that's where we take

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:48.300
our cattle, and that's
the reason why--

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:54.000
one of reasons, and why we
extended all over Western

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:55.590
and Central Africa.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.110
And when we embraced
Islam in the beginning

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:01.350
of the 11th century, and then
we started spreading Islam,

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:02.940
and also used the
other reason that

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:08.610
explains why we spread
over from the Senegal delta

00:04:08.610 --> 00:04:13.780
all the way to
Nigeria and Sudan.

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:17.110
So this is the Fulai language.

00:04:17.110 --> 00:04:19.750
Like I mentioned earlier,
there are 50 million--

00:04:19.750 --> 00:04:23.470
at least 50 million
Fulanis in Africa

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:25.210
and around the world at least.

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:28.805
And we speak different dialects
of the Fulani language.

00:04:28.805 --> 00:04:33.850
It's called Fulfulde if you are
on the Eastern side of Africa,

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:38.720
starting in Mali and
all the way to Sudan.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:43.480
But it's called Pular if you
are in Senegal, or Guinea,

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:45.980
or Sierra Leone area.

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:48.530
Fulfulde-- the reason why it's
called Fulfulde in the others

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:50.010
regions-- basically,
Fulfulde means

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:52.640
dialect in the Fulani language.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:55.444
So basically the
version of the Pular

00:04:55.444 --> 00:04:57.860
that's spoken by the other
people is just called dialects,

00:04:57.860 --> 00:04:59.330
and then that name stuck.

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:02.870
And the language actually is
referred to now, globally,

00:05:02.870 --> 00:05:04.040
as Fulfulde.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:05.900
Most people know
Fulfulde, and only

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:09.350
a few people except maybe people
from French speaking countries,

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:13.120
refer to the language as Pular.

00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:15.130
So as you can see
here, it's part

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:18.730
of the North Atlantic branch
of the Niger-Congo as Wolof

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:20.100
and Serer.

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:24.460
And it's spoken at least
in two dozen countries,

00:05:24.460 --> 00:05:26.230
and it's recognized
by the African Union

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:28.480
as one of the official
languages that will eventually

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.860
be used in addition to English,
French, Portuguese, Spanish,

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:34.510
and then we'll have Swahili.

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:37.150
And also in the ECWAS, which is
the economic. community of West

00:05:37.150 --> 00:05:41.260
African States, has
16 countries that are

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.250
members of the organizations.

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:46.000
And Fulani is one of
the languages that

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.250
they looking into, because
basically in West Africa,

00:05:48.250 --> 00:05:50.530
we have three big
languages that can serve

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:54.550
to unite those countries--
we have the Fulani language,

00:05:54.550 --> 00:05:57.460
we have the Hausa language,
and the Mandingo language.

00:05:57.460 --> 00:05:59.260
And those are the
transnational languages

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.440
in West Africa, spoken
in multiple countries.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:05.410
And originally the Fulani
language was written--

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:08.560
as you remember, I mentioned
the Fulanis embraced Islam

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:11.200
in the early 11th century--

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:14.350
and then we started using
Arabic, the Arabic script,

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:17.200
to write the Fulani language.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:19.750
And we used it all over,
but there was no standard.

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:22.450
So each region or each
person or each group

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.670
was writing the
Fulani language based

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:26.560
on their own understanding.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:30.296
Because the problem
is that we have sounds

00:06:30.296 --> 00:06:32.170
that are specific to
the Fulani language that

00:06:32.170 --> 00:06:34.480
are non-existent in Arabic.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:38.230
So there was a--

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:40.630
how to create the
correspondence for the letters,

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:42.610
the sounds that
we have, in Arabic

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:44.009
that don't exist in there.

00:06:44.009 --> 00:06:45.550
And then the fact
that the Arabs have

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:47.740
some sounds that we don't need.

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:54.520
So people were using some
of those letters in Arabic

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:57.030
as a correspondent
one of the sounds that

00:06:57.030 --> 00:07:00.100
existed in our language,
but it's not standardized.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:02.410
So every person was
doing their own thing.

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:04.390
And I explain the
story of actually how

00:07:04.390 --> 00:07:07.420
this whole thing started
that we'll get to later on.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:09.940
And the reason, in
the '70s, people

00:07:09.940 --> 00:07:13.890
started using the Latin
alphabet, but also the problem

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.090
with that is, each
country, or each region,

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:17.640
was using their own standard.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:21.250
In Guinea, actually,
during the first regime,

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:25.540
they used to teach the
national languages in Guinea.

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:27.670
But we were using
an alphabet that

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:30.280
was different from any
of the other countries--

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:31.090
the Latin alphabet.

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:33.400
So for example,
for the sound bah,

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:36.580
we were using bh, while
in other countries

00:07:36.580 --> 00:07:41.950
they were using a sign that
looks like a 6, the number six.

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:45.760
So there was a
problem also reading

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:50.000
what's written in Guinea versus
what's written in Senegal

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.025
or Mali, for example.

00:07:57.420 --> 00:08:00.300
And also one thing that I can
say about the Fulani language--

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:04.410
it's one of the most widely
spoken languages in Guinea.

00:08:04.410 --> 00:08:09.660
It's actually the lingua franca
in the central parts of Guinea

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:14.910
all the way to the region--
the lowlands toward the ocean.

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:17.712
And also in Cameroon, northern
Cameroon in the Adamawa region,

00:08:17.712 --> 00:08:18.670
it's the lingua franca.

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.690
It's one of the most widely
spoken language there.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:25.560
And the fact that there
were these problems using

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:31.020
different sets of letters
to write the language

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:34.750
is actually what
will lead us to this.

00:08:34.750 --> 00:08:39.840
My dad lived in region--

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:42.188
unfortunately, I don't
have a map of Guinea,

00:08:42.188 --> 00:08:45.160
but in Guinea we have
four natural regions.

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:47.350
And the Fulani people
mostly live mostly

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:49.000
in the mountain regions.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
But my dad moved from
there to go and start

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:53.830
a business in the
forest region, which

00:08:53.830 --> 00:08:57.700
was about 800 kilometers away.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:08:59.910
And you know, Fulanis
being nomadic people,

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:01.330
so that's how the
spread all over.

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:04.360
Even though they abandoned
cattle herding, some of them

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:08.140
did, but they're still
engaged in other businesses

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:11.860
by traveling to other
regions and other countries.

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:13.840
So the way people
stayed in touch

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:16.900
with their relatives
is by sending letters

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:21.640
to their relatives, and usually
they will write it in Arabic,

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.560
using the Arabic letters.

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:25.810
And since there was
no standard, there

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:27.550
were only a few people
who could actually

00:09:27.550 --> 00:09:30.400
read a letter for someone.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.980
So my dad was one
of those people who,

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:36.260
if people received letters from
their relatives back in Fouta,

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:41.110
they will send the letters to
him so that he can read them.

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:44.110
So that's how we got into
reading those letters.

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:48.640
We learned it from our dad, and
then we got really good at it.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.580
And then at the end, he
started giving us the letters

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:53.590
to read for the people.

00:09:53.590 --> 00:09:56.184
But what we noticed is
that, like I said earlier,

00:09:56.184 --> 00:09:57.100
there was no standard.

00:09:57.100 --> 00:09:59.140
So most of the time
you were just guessing.

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:00.640
Because you know the language.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:02.260
If you see something,
the word, you

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:04.690
can actually guess what the
person was trying to write,

00:10:04.690 --> 00:10:06.930
even though it's
not exactly how you

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:08.350
think that they would write it.

00:10:08.350 --> 00:10:10.120
So that's how I got
to asking my dad,

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:13.840
how come we don't have
our own writing system,

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:17.860
so that we can write in a
way that everyone can read?

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:20.920
Without having to guess,
without having any problems.

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:24.430
And he told us that we
don't have a writing system,

00:10:24.430 --> 00:10:28.840
and then that's how I told him
that maybe that's something

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:32.530
that we would looking
into creating.

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:35.650
And my mom also had a
rice bar restaurant--

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:37.630
a small restaurant
next to the market--

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:40.440
where I used to hang
out after school.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:43.010
And that's where I met
this guy who had traveled

00:10:43.010 --> 00:10:44.590
a lot around West Africa.

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:47.004
And he used to tell me a
lot about the Fulani people.

00:10:47.004 --> 00:10:49.420
He's the one who first told
me that the Fulanis are prison

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:51.790
all over, because I used
to think Fulanis are only

00:10:51.790 --> 00:10:54.250
present in Guinea.

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:57.190
But he said, because we are
present all over Africa,

00:10:57.190 --> 00:11:01.000
we speak different dialects
and we write differently.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.310
And then he said that
people-- they've been looking

00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:06.250
into unifying the languages,
and then you start reciting name

00:11:06.250 --> 00:11:07.210
of people--

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:11.220
well-known peoples in
the Fulani community.

00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:12.790
And he told me all
of those people

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:15.520
have looked into creating
an alphabet so that they

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:17.500
can unify the language
that they-- but

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:19.060
have not been able to.

00:11:19.060 --> 00:11:23.620
So that combined with what
happened with my dad really

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:28.190
motivated me into looking
into ways to creating

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:29.710
an alphabet for our language.

00:11:29.710 --> 00:11:34.570
That's actually how the idea
and the motivation came about.

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:37.150
And then I was always
with my brother.

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:38.630
And then he talked
to me about it.

00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:40.280
And then we started the process.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:41.690
And this is how we started.

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:44.110
Sometime after school, we
would go into our room,

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:46.630
we started drawing
lines, and then

00:11:46.630 --> 00:11:50.830
we'll pick whatever looks like
a letter to us from those signs,

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:52.080
as you can see here.

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:54.730
Or the other method
that we could use

00:11:54.730 --> 00:11:57.510
is that I would think
of a letter or a sound,

00:11:57.510 --> 00:12:01.510
and I would imagine how it would
look like when it's written.

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:04.030
And then I'll draw
based on that.

00:12:04.030 --> 00:12:07.210
And that's how we ended up
getting all the letters.

00:12:07.210 --> 00:12:08.900
We got 27.

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:10.990
But later it would be
28, because we later

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:13.847
discovered there's one
more sound that we needed.

00:12:13.847 --> 00:12:14.930
So we added that later on.

00:12:14.930 --> 00:12:18.730
But originally we
had 27 letters.

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:22.750
And then when we created
all those letters,

00:12:22.750 --> 00:12:26.920
we told my dad that we
finally created an alphabet,

00:12:26.920 --> 00:12:29.690
and he didn't believe us.

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:31.780
So he called one
of his relatives

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:33.685
who used to work
for the government,

00:12:33.685 --> 00:12:38.900
and then told that guy to come,
because his sons, his kids have

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:40.770
informed him that they
created an alphabet,

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:42.730
bu the thinks
they're just playing.

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:45.320
So this guy came, and then
he started testing us.

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:47.380
So he would ask me
to leave the room

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:49.920
and then he will tell
my brother to write

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:51.820
a word using the new alphabet.

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:54.950
And then my brother would write
the word, and then I'll come

00:12:54.950 --> 00:12:57.409
and then he'll ask me to read
it, and then I would read it,

00:12:57.409 --> 00:12:58.991
and it would be
exactly what he asked.

00:12:58.991 --> 00:13:00.370
And then he did the same thing.

00:13:00.370 --> 00:13:02.170
He asked my brother
to leave the room.

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:02.980
My brother left.

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:04.870
And then he asked me
to write something.

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:08.860
He asked me to write one of
the hardest words that he could

00:13:08.860 --> 00:13:11.110
think of in Pular, which
is [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:13.600
and then I wrote it, and then
my brother came and read it,

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:16.180
and then he turned to
my dad, and he's like,

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:18.910
I think these guys are
onto something here.

00:13:18.910 --> 00:13:25.090
And basically that's how
the writing system started.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:25.840
The ADLaM.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:28.690
But back then it
wasn't called ADLaM.

00:13:28.690 --> 00:13:29.770
We created the alphabet.

00:13:29.770 --> 00:13:33.690
We started working on it.

00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:36.510
And then we started teaching--
the first person that we taught

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:38.170
was my sister.

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:41.740
Go on to the next slide.

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:42.750
This is her.

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:46.790
And this is the one of the
first books that we used.

00:13:46.790 --> 00:13:51.700
This is actually her
writing back then.

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:55.712
So this is how we
started teaching people.

00:13:55.712 --> 00:13:58.170
We didn't have a name for the
alphabet, it was really hard,

00:13:58.170 --> 00:14:00.545
and we just kept calling it
Bindi Pular which basically--

00:14:00.545 --> 00:14:03.260
literally means the
writing, the Pular writing.

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:04.610
And then we taught her.

00:14:04.610 --> 00:14:07.010
And after that we started
going around to the market.

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:08.030
The next slide.

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:12.550
We started teaching
in the community.

00:14:12.550 --> 00:14:15.430
And my dad used to own
a shop in the market,

00:14:15.430 --> 00:14:17.950
and that's where we
started, because there were

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:19.869
many Fulanis in the market.

00:14:19.869 --> 00:14:21.160
So we would go there and teach.

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:22.850
This is me and my brother.

00:14:22.850 --> 00:14:24.530
My brother is in
the middle here,

00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:26.710
in the yellow and blue jacket.

00:14:26.710 --> 00:14:29.710
I'm in the back.

00:14:29.710 --> 00:14:32.150
And those are some of the few
people that we taught then.

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:37.940
And two years later,
this is the picture

00:14:37.940 --> 00:14:40.330
after we had already
created the alphabet.

00:14:40.330 --> 00:14:44.650
And then the next slide
shows how the alphabet looked

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:45.850
in the 1990's.

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:48.076
This is how we used to write it.

00:14:48.076 --> 00:14:49.450
And when we created
the alphabet,

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:52.030
because we were heavily
influenced by Arabic,

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:54.370
we started from right to left.

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:56.490
But also since we
are going to school,

00:14:56.490 --> 00:15:00.040
we are also influenced
by the French language.

00:15:00.040 --> 00:15:02.950
Instead of using diacritical
marks as in Arabic

00:15:02.950 --> 00:15:08.410
to mark the vowels, we use
actual vowels in our language.

00:15:08.410 --> 00:15:11.860
Because our language is
not the same as Arabic.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:13.930
Arabic only has three
vowels, but we actually

00:15:13.930 --> 00:15:16.450
have five vowels, as in English.

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:18.610
Actually, we used
to think we had six,

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:21.510
but it turns out
we only had five.

00:15:21.510 --> 00:15:23.260
So that's why we write
from right to left.

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:26.200
And then we originally
also, all the letters

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:28.720
were joined, as in Arabic.

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:30.430
So this is how we
started writing it.

00:15:30.430 --> 00:15:33.760
And these are the
first manuscripts.

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:37.830
And then we started
writing books.

00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:39.240
Basically what we
were doing back

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:41.380
then is, the books
that we were studying,

00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:43.890
either religious books or
books from our schools,

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:47.460
we would translate them
into our language in Pular,

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:50.805
and write them using
the new alphabet.

00:15:50.805 --> 00:15:52.930
And these are books that
we'll then show to people.

00:15:55.550 --> 00:15:57.330
And then after the--

00:15:57.330 --> 00:16:01.310
because few years
later, sense we

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:03.850
had had a lot of
practice writing,

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:06.470
so then we started
writing this way.

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:09.080
Experimenting writing
the letters separately,

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:11.240
as you can see on
the next slide.

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:14.090
Then I started writing
books with the letters

00:16:14.090 --> 00:16:15.590
not joined, actually.

00:16:15.590 --> 00:16:17.060
You can't really
tell here, maybe,

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:18.260
because the image
is not that good.

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:20.350
But these actually--
these letters that are not

00:16:20.350 --> 00:16:21.600
joined, as you can see.

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:23.390
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:16:23.390 --> 00:16:25.340
So we started
experimenting, and then we

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:29.960
noticed that this actually
was easier for people to read.

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:31.120
So we continued on that.

00:16:31.120 --> 00:16:37.100
And then I'll let my brother
talk about the next slide.

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:39.100
IBRAHIM BARRY: Like
my brother said,

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:44.460
we have many different phases of
the evolution of ADLaM script.

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:51.410
So the first one we call the
first generation of book.

00:16:51.410 --> 00:16:54.980
We call this the first
generation of book, as he said.

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:57.810
It was just the
book and the stories

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.860
we used to learn from
my dad and my mom.

00:17:00.860 --> 00:17:04.069
We used to write them
and go around the city

00:17:04.069 --> 00:17:05.150
and teach people.

00:17:05.150 --> 00:17:07.339
And people really liked them.

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:14.540
So by the time we move to the
second generation of book,

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:19.050
we started thinking about the
language, about the structure.

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:21.619
About the laws in the language.

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:25.220
So we continued teaching
people in the market,

00:17:25.220 --> 00:17:27.589
around the city, every
time when we come back

00:17:27.589 --> 00:17:30.410
from school and
during our break.

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:33.180
We used to teach
people all the time.

00:17:33.180 --> 00:17:36.560
So by the second
generation of book,

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:39.020
we have a lot of different book.

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:42.350
But the third generation
of book started in 2000,

00:17:42.350 --> 00:17:47.570
when I moved to the University
of Conakry, in my country,

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:49.370
in the capital city.

00:17:49.370 --> 00:17:53.270
When I moved there, I
started an organization.

00:17:53.270 --> 00:17:56.270
Because all the books from
the first through to second

00:17:56.270 --> 00:18:00.080
generation, of them was
writing by my brother.

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:04.430
I used to help him
teaching around the city.

00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:06.470
So when I moved
to the University,

00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:08.850
I started talking to
some of my friend.

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:11.810
They were really interested
in teaching people.

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:15.260
And so they started
working with us.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:19.410
From the University we
have five different groups.

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:24.080
We have people going for
medical school, the people going

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:25.400
for engineering school.

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:29.070
We have different
project, so we just

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:35.300
write books that really
affected the life of people.

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:37.430
So when we started
this kind of book,

00:18:37.430 --> 00:18:40.260
the script become very poPular.

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:42.530
So like this one--

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:45.830
some of my student
at the University,

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:47.550
who was going for
medical school,

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:51.200
they started writing
books in our language.

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:55.720
How a woman can take care
of her kid, since he--

00:18:55.720 --> 00:19:01.530
when he sees that her pregnancy
into her kid is growing up.

00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:04.685
The kind of food you
have to give them,

00:19:04.685 --> 00:19:08.150
how to take care of them, how
to clean their [INAUDIBLE].

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:10.160
So we started teaching people.

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:12.830
And those book
become very poPular,

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:15.050
and people was
very happy to read.

00:19:15.050 --> 00:19:19.850
Because more than 80% does
not know how to read and write

00:19:19.850 --> 00:19:23.630
in English language back then--

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:25.365
in French language,
in my country.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:32.070
We also wrote many
different book--

00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:35.190
how to clean water,
because usually people

00:19:35.190 --> 00:19:39.870
take water from the well,
so we give them how--

00:19:39.870 --> 00:19:40.900
teach them.

00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:45.090
Back then I was doing chemical
engineering for my first two

00:19:45.090 --> 00:19:47.040
years at the University.

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:50.370
So we learned the process,
and we developed a process

00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:54.570
and teach them and show
them how to make those tool.

00:19:54.570 --> 00:19:57.060
So around the country--

00:19:57.060 --> 00:20:02.010
so after that, we
started a newspaper.

00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:04.630
I started a newspaper in Guinea
called [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:06.300
or The Pen.

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:10.570
So I used to write all
the news, all the time.

00:20:10.570 --> 00:20:14.100
And whenever people
read, they use

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:17.760
sometimes even to
have ears, to cry,

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:20.400
because they know now
how to read and write.

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:26.460
Also we teach people
how to have basic math

00:20:26.460 --> 00:20:28.290
to take care of their business.

00:20:28.290 --> 00:20:31.740
Because usually a lot of
people put money together.

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:36.240
They will go to
Asia, buy goods, when

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:40.230
they come they have to find
someone who know how to read

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:43.830
and write in French
language to help

00:20:43.830 --> 00:20:48.810
them divided this stuff before
they start selling them.

00:20:48.810 --> 00:20:52.860
So I teach them how to
do that by themselves.

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:55.620
We give them basic
math, how to divide

00:20:55.620 --> 00:20:58.200
[INAUDIBLE] stuff
when they bring them

00:20:58.200 --> 00:21:01.990
from Asia or Morocco.

00:21:01.990 --> 00:21:04.470
And I started having
problem with the government

00:21:04.470 --> 00:21:07.650
because I was teaching
a lot of people.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:15.120
And also I was one of
the leader of the student

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:19.010
movement at the
university, I was

00:21:19.010 --> 00:21:21.450
the president of that movement.

00:21:21.450 --> 00:21:25.840
They called [INAUDIBLE]--
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] Guinean.

00:21:25.840 --> 00:21:30.330
So finally I end up going
to prison for three month.

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:33.660
So when I come out,
I continue teaching.

00:21:33.660 --> 00:21:37.950
And I used to have a lot
of issues after that.

00:21:37.950 --> 00:21:39.850
I went even to Senegal.

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:43.350
I traveled to Senegal,
continue teaching here

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:45.930
at the University
of Senegal with some

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:51.180
of my friend, who taught back
home who move also to Senegal.

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:54.300
They have the same
problem I had in Guinea.

00:21:54.300 --> 00:21:58.830
So they was looking
to put them in jail.

00:21:58.830 --> 00:22:01.080
So they fled to Senegal.

00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:02.910
So I went back to
see them there.

00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:05.280
We continued teaching.

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:07.650
When I went to
Senegal, what really

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:11.360
struck I went to the market
with some of these people.

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:14.580
I found the book I was
writing in Guinea already

00:22:14.580 --> 00:22:16.740
in the market with ladies.

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:20.790
So I started talking to
some of those ladies.

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:22.810
They told me, can you read this?

00:22:22.810 --> 00:22:25.660
I say maybe,
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:27.900
And one of them say,
I can teach you.

00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:29.220
I really like this book.

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:31.350
It's really helping me.

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:34.020
And I ask them how
did you got this book?

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:38.610
Because they said, so a
lady is bringing the palm

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:42.380
oil from Guinea, she is the one
who brought those book here.

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:44.310
She is the one who
is teaching us.

00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:48.630
But right now, whenever someone
takes something from me,

00:22:48.630 --> 00:22:50.520
I write down.

00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:52.920
I am following all my
business with this.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:54.660
And it's really helping me.

00:22:54.660 --> 00:22:58.510
And I already started teaching
people classes in the market.

00:22:58.510 --> 00:23:00.750
The other ladies.

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:03.830
In 2007 I moved to
the United State.

00:23:03.830 --> 00:23:06.120
When I come here,
my biggest goal

00:23:06.120 --> 00:23:09.960
was to computerize
the writing system.

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:13.445
Because back in the days, I used
to write everything by hand.

00:23:13.445 --> 00:23:15.870
It was very difficult whenever.

00:23:15.870 --> 00:23:18.720
You have a mistake
in one page, you're

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:20.890
going to lose all that page.

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:25.770
You have to write again,
before you print the books.

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:29.680
So when I come here
in 2007, I talk

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:34.470
to some of my community members
in New York if they could help.

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:37.920
We're going to have
a software that can

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:40.620
help us write in a computer.

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:43.230
So when I come
back to Portland--

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:45.615
when I come to Portland
to see my brother--

00:23:45.615 --> 00:23:48.120
he figure out to find
a company in Seattle

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.910
that could done that.

00:23:49.910 --> 00:23:51.690
Then we discuss with them.

00:23:51.690 --> 00:23:55.380
So we come back, we
didn't have the money.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:57.840
So we have to work
seven month straight

00:23:57.840 --> 00:24:02.180
and save all the money,
100%, and make the software.

00:24:02.180 --> 00:24:06.330
We made the software and
we bought some computers.

00:24:06.330 --> 00:24:10.950
My brother, in 2007,
went to Guinea.

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:14.970
In 2008, he went to Guinea.

00:24:14.970 --> 00:24:17.130
He brought some
of those computers

00:24:17.130 --> 00:24:20.070
and teach people how to use
them, how to write book,

00:24:20.070 --> 00:24:22.580
and how to edit them.

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:28.420
But this font was on
the Arabic code point.

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:30.550
So we have a lot of
problem using them,

00:24:30.550 --> 00:24:34.120
but it makes everything easier.

00:24:34.120 --> 00:24:38.890
And we was producing a lot
of books, a lot of newspaper.

00:24:38.890 --> 00:24:44.420
And we bought a
lot of computers.

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:47.880
One of the guy in New
York gave many computers.

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:51.390
We send it back home, we started
an organization here called

00:24:51.390 --> 00:24:52.470
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:57.120
We bought computers, we send for
the teachers, for the writers

00:24:57.120 --> 00:24:59.040
back home.

00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:01.650
But we still have challenges.

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:04.980
Because we teach a lot of
people, and the internet

00:25:04.980 --> 00:25:06.750
is coming back home.

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:10.440
Every villages-- they have
cell phone everywhere,

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:13.650
and people started
calling us all the time.

00:25:13.650 --> 00:25:15.300
How can I write this?

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:17.260
How can I text?

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:20.850
I said, we don't have
the solution right now,

00:25:20.850 --> 00:25:25.080
but we are doing
some research on it.

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:30.450
That how I started learning
the different process

00:25:30.450 --> 00:25:31.330
until we got--

00:25:31.330 --> 00:25:36.640
I discover, in order
to be in this system,

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:39.000
to be in Unicode phase.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:43.260
So this is peoples
teaching back home.

00:25:43.260 --> 00:25:47.530
One of these guys, who used
to live in New York, he's--

00:25:47.530 --> 00:25:52.620
he just moved back home
in Africa to teach people.

00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:59.160
Because he has a Master's degree
in one of the Arab countries,

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.300
Syria.

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:02.370
So he will come to New York.

00:26:02.370 --> 00:26:03.340
He went to school.

00:26:03.340 --> 00:26:07.720
He learned the English
languages, and went back home.

00:26:07.720 --> 00:26:10.990
Just, he said, he's moving
back just to teach people

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:12.880
how to read and write.

00:26:12.880 --> 00:26:15.880
And they put him
in contact with us.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:18.960
We taught him how to read
and write the script.

00:26:18.960 --> 00:26:22.920
And he found this is the
easiest way to teach people.

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:24.645
The best way is
in their language.

00:26:24.645 --> 00:26:28.140
He have taught many different
people around Africa.

00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:34.230
So spatially, we focusing a lot
in womans, because most of them

00:26:34.230 --> 00:26:36.040
don't go to school.

00:26:36.040 --> 00:26:42.090
And children, who parent doesn't
have the mean to go to school.

00:26:42.090 --> 00:26:45.340
So we teach them at least
how to read and write.

00:26:45.340 --> 00:26:47.700
And then we started newspapers.

00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:49.940
We call this newspaper
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:26:49.940 --> 00:26:52.800
Everything going around
the country and Africa.

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:56.890
Is monthly newspaper, it's
still going out every year.

00:26:56.890 --> 00:27:02.430
And right now we have some
of very outstanding brothers

00:27:02.430 --> 00:27:04.740
who have finished school.

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:07.710
They went for law
school and journalists--

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:10.440
they are the ones who are
running this newspaper back

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:11.250
home.

00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:13.970
But before, I am the
one who started it.

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:15.960
I was writing everything.

00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:20.620
So now we have people
doing this back home.

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:25.240
So we're still working on
the script and developing it.

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:30.880
And going forward, we have
people writing biology book,

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:32.680
physics, mathematics.

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:35.680
Right now, the basic,
to teach people.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:40.960
To give them a little
basic in their language

