00:31:09.132 --> 00:31:10.840
ABDOULAYE BARRY: Just
one thing before he

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:12.449
start talking about the thing.

00:31:12.449 --> 00:31:14.740
Remember how I told you when
we created the alphabet we

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:16.300
couldn't come up with a name?

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:21.490
So imagine, since the
1990s, all the way til 2012,

00:31:21.490 --> 00:31:22.434
we didn't have a name.

00:31:22.434 --> 00:31:24.850
We actually experimented, we
thought about different names

00:31:24.850 --> 00:31:25.870
on how to call the alphabet.

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:28.120
Whenever people ask us, what's
the name of the alphabet?

00:31:28.120 --> 00:31:30.203
We just call Bindi Pular,
which is writing system.

00:31:30.203 --> 00:31:32.800
Or, people would call
it the writing system

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:36.090
that came from N'Zerekore,
which is our hometown where

00:31:36.090 --> 00:31:37.420
we were born.

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:39.730
But one day,
because the alphabet

00:31:39.730 --> 00:31:42.040
became so poPular in
Guinea, so the instructors

00:31:42.040 --> 00:31:43.780
they gathered one
day and they say,

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:46.610
we have to give this
alphabet a name.

00:31:46.610 --> 00:31:49.640
And they found a
very simple thing.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:50.920
It's unbelievable.

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:54.580
Because they just took the first
four letters of the alphabet,

00:31:54.580 --> 00:31:55.789
and called it.

00:31:55.789 --> 00:31:58.330
And we couldn't believe that,
we couldn't even think of that.

00:31:58.330 --> 00:31:59.290
As simple as that.

00:31:59.290 --> 00:32:01.780
They call it ADLaM--
ah, dah, lah, mah.

00:32:01.780 --> 00:32:05.740
And they gave you a
perfect definition,

00:32:05.740 --> 00:32:07.720
which is the alphabet
that will prevent

00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:09.010
the people from disappearing.

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:12.790
Because that was
one of the things

00:32:12.790 --> 00:32:17.110
that most African languages
are confronted with.

00:32:17.110 --> 00:32:18.880
You know, there's
French language

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:21.010
in Africa, which is--
actually, in Guinea,

00:32:21.010 --> 00:32:22.570
that's the official language.

00:32:22.570 --> 00:32:24.740
The language of the instruction.

00:32:24.740 --> 00:32:27.430
But in our homes, we
speak our own languages.

00:32:27.430 --> 00:32:29.800
In the markets, we
speak our own languages.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:32.080
But if you go to school,
you learn French.

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:35.530
And the government--
everything is done in French.

00:32:35.530 --> 00:32:40.240
So there is-- our languages
are threatened by the French,

00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:42.520
by the French language
or English language.

00:32:42.520 --> 00:32:43.780
IBRAHIM BARRY: Or Arabic.

00:32:43.780 --> 00:32:46.060
ABDOULAYE BARRY: Or
Arabic language, also.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:49.690
So that's why it made perfect
sense for the alphabet

00:32:49.690 --> 00:32:52.510
to be a way to protect our
language from disappearing.

00:32:52.510 --> 00:32:56.050
Because if the language is
really the vehicle of culture,

00:32:56.050 --> 00:32:57.430
like we say it is--

00:32:57.430 --> 00:33:00.659
because if your language dies,
your culture dies with it.

00:33:00.659 --> 00:33:02.200
Because there are
certain things that

00:33:02.200 --> 00:33:08.990
are specific to cultures that
can only be shared within--

00:33:08.990 --> 00:33:12.460
with codes or words
in that culture.

00:33:12.460 --> 00:33:14.530
So if you lose
the language, that

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:18.430
means the culture is eventually
[INAUDIBLE] to disappear.

00:33:18.430 --> 00:33:20.840
And if the culture disappears,
that means the people.

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:23.020
Not the physical
people, but the people

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:25.030
as in their culture,
civilization,

00:33:25.030 --> 00:33:26.320
and their history.

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:27.730
All of that goes with it.

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:30.280
So they came up
with the name ADLaM.

00:33:30.280 --> 00:33:31.870
And it was perfect.

00:33:31.870 --> 00:33:33.630
It was like, we
couldn't believe it.

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:38.290
And it was perfect
timing because we

00:33:38.290 --> 00:33:40.900
were about to start the
process with Unicode.

00:33:40.900 --> 00:33:44.200
And it would have been awkward
for us to submit a proposal

00:33:44.200 --> 00:33:46.880
and not even have a
name for the alphabet.

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:49.720
So when I moved here, I
started contacting Unicode.

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:54.010
