it doesn't correspond well.

00:40:00.850 --> 00:40:02.500
The alphabet isn't
very well suited

00:40:02.500 --> 00:40:04.660
to the pronunciation system.

00:40:04.660 --> 00:40:09.100
So I really appreciate
what you did as children.

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:12.190
But one of the
difficulties that I

00:40:12.190 --> 00:40:14.140
faced in trying to
propose a spelling

00:40:14.140 --> 00:40:17.980
reform for Brazilian
Portuguese is

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:22.220
how phonetic versus how phonemic
do you want language to be?

00:40:22.220 --> 00:40:24.430
So, obviously I don't
speak your language,

00:40:24.430 --> 00:40:27.700
but an example in English
would be the word "better".

00:40:27.700 --> 00:40:30.810
So that sound in better, no
word starts with that sound,

00:40:30.810 --> 00:40:33.610
it's not really a t, we don't
say beh-ter, it's not a d,

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:37.450
we don't say beh-der,
like in David, beh-der.

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:38.860
It's some intermediate
sound that

00:40:38.860 --> 00:40:41.590
only exists between
a stressed syllable

00:40:41.590 --> 00:40:43.670
and an unstressed syllable.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:46.000
That's why we say photo,
but we say photographer,

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:47.860
we don't say "pho-dographer."

00:40:47.860 --> 00:40:49.420
So this is like a
really subtle thing

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:52.710
for, I would imagine
someone, who's 11 years old,

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:55.070
to appreciate that.

00:40:55.070 --> 00:40:57.940
But you have to teach the
language to other people.

00:40:57.940 --> 00:41:02.200
So is this alphabet--
is it very phonetic?

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:03.950
Is it really the way
you pronounce it?

00:41:03.950 --> 00:41:07.390
Or is it more abstract,
like you use a symbol

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:10.150
that maybe some people will
pronounce it one way in one

00:41:10.150 --> 00:41:12.670
situation, maybe they'll
pronounce it another way

00:41:12.670 --> 00:41:14.020
in another context?

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:17.040
Maybe someone in one region will
pronounce the symbol one way.

00:41:17.040 --> 00:41:20.110
Maybe someone in another region
will pronounce it another way,

00:41:20.110 --> 00:41:24.650
like "bet-ter" in
London Or "bed-ah."

00:41:24.650 --> 00:41:27.700
How closely phonetic
is this alphabet?

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:30.050
ABDOULAYE BARRY: It's
very phonetic, actually.

00:41:30.050 --> 00:41:32.200
That's actually the
thing that makes it easy.

00:41:32.200 --> 00:41:35.410
Because we say the difference
between the alphabet

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:38.470
for the Fulani
language, and English,

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:43.420
and the Latin alphabet for the
English language, is actually,

00:41:43.420 --> 00:41:45.580
we write what we say.

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:47.412
It's exactly the
way we pronounce it.

00:41:47.412 --> 00:41:48.370
That's how we write it.

00:41:48.370 --> 00:41:52.120
There is no sound there
that can be tweaked or--

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:54.640
is very phonetic, basically.

00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:56.940
ABDOULAYE BARRY: If it's a
dah, you see it written dah,

00:41:56.940 --> 00:41:58.400
it's going to be dah.

00:41:58.400 --> 00:42:00.850
Whether it's in
Guinea or whether it's

00:42:00.850 --> 00:42:05.530
in RCA-- in the Central
African Republic, CAR.

00:42:05.530 --> 00:42:06.042
