things about ADLaM.

00:48:56.170 --> 00:49:01.360
Because as you said, we
have Fulfulde being spoken

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:03.550
across thousands of miles.

00:49:03.550 --> 00:49:07.720
And what ADLaM has helped us
is standardize the language.

00:49:07.720 --> 00:49:11.107
Because right now,
originally at the beginning,

00:49:11.107 --> 00:49:13.190
when we would talk to
someone who is from Nigeria,

00:49:13.190 --> 00:49:15.315
we would have difficulties
communicating with them,

00:49:15.315 --> 00:49:17.410
because they speak in
a different dialect.

00:49:17.410 --> 00:49:21.510
But now, all the people
who are learning ADLaM,

00:49:21.510 --> 00:49:25.990
or who are involved
in the ADLaM program,

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:28.040
we all understand each other.

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:29.620
So usually when we
edit the language,

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:31.805
we are not only
using one dialect,

00:49:31.805 --> 00:49:34.180
because the reason why we have
so many different dialects

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:36.970
is also because we are so
mobile, we are nomadic people.

00:49:36.970 --> 00:49:40.150
So wherever we go, based on the
environment, and the people who

00:49:40.150 --> 00:49:44.230
are there, we will borrow new
words from that community,

00:49:44.230 --> 00:49:46.000
and out into the
Fulani language.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.680
But what we are
doing right now is--

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:52.240
the standardization just means
going back to the original.

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:54.820
Because we all speak
the same language.

00:49:54.820 --> 00:49:56.780
Structure-wise
it's all the same,

00:49:56.780 --> 00:49:59.480
it's just the words that
are usually different.

00:49:59.480 --> 00:50:02.220
So we usually-- if, for example,
something is called in Guinea

00:50:02.220 --> 00:50:03.700
in a certain way,
