doing research on the
language, we already--

00:51:56.630 --> 00:52:02.120
in Guinea we already have lost
the name of the seven days

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:03.390
in our language.

00:52:03.390 --> 00:52:06.200
We used to call them in Arabic.

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:13.740
So in my traveling, I saw
one of the group of Fulani

00:52:13.740 --> 00:52:19.540
who still have the
seven days of the week,

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:21.350
in the Fulani language.

00:52:21.350 --> 00:52:25.760
And I use that one in all the
book, in all the newspaper.

00:52:25.760 --> 00:52:29.330
And right now, I can say
most of the Fulani in Guinea

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:33.890
are using that one,
instead of the Arabic one.

00:52:33.890 --> 00:52:35.080
That how we are working.

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:40.850
And people really like
the idea using whatever

00:52:40.850 --> 00:52:42.070
we have in the language.

00:52:42.070 --> 00:52:44.080
Not to borrow that one.

00:52:44.080 --> 00:52:44.970
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:44.970 --> 00:52:46.095
ABDOULAYE BARRY: Thank you.

00:52:46.095 --> 00:52:48.800
And the other thing that is--

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:53.840
we was-- even though Fulani was
written in Arabic many years,

00:52:53.840 --> 00:52:55.460
and everyone was
just writing based

00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:57.900
on their own understanding.

00:52:57.900 --> 00:52:59.270
So there was no standard.

00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:03.140
But what ADLaM is doing
is helping with that.

00:53:03.140 --> 00:53:06.180
So if you've written something--
and since the environment also

00:53:06.180 --> 00:53:10.450
informs, in many ways, how
people see certain things,

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:12.830
or how words are
added to the language.

00:53:12.830 --> 00:53:14.330
For example, there
are certain trees

00:53:14.330 --> 00:53:17.225
that exist in Guinea that
don't exist in Cameroon.

00:53:20.155 --> 00:53:22.640
But the Cameroonians
know of that

00:53:22.640 --> 00:53:24.680
only through reading
French books.

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:27.270
So probably they
call that in French.

00:53:27.270 --> 00:53:29.630
But since the trees
in Guinea will just

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:32.710
use the word the name that's
used in Guinea for that tree,

00:53:32.710 --> 00:53:35.270
so the Cameroonian
Fulanis don't have

00:53:35.270 --> 00:53:36.665
to use the French word anymore.

00:53:36.665 --> 00:53:37.790
But that's how we're doing.

00:53:37.790 --> 00:53:41.540
So basically what the
language is the same.

00:53:41.540 --> 00:53:44.420
But it's just the borrowed
words or the environment

00:53:44.420 --> 00:53:46.760
that's creating some
of the differences.

00:53:46.760 --> 00:53:49.730
And also there are some changes,
because where the Fulanis are

00:53:49.730 --> 00:53:53.630
a very tiny minority, or where
the language has been heavily

00:53:53.630 --> 00:53:55.920
influenced by people
who actually learned it,

00:53:55.920 --> 00:53:58.820
but who are not originally
Fulanis, like in certain areas

00:53:58.820 --> 00:54:01.310
of Cameroon, if the structure
has changed a little bit,

00:54:01.310 --> 00:54:03.350
we can actually tell
when we sees it written.

00:54:03.350 --> 00:54:05.660
So we just correct the grammar.

00:54:05.660 --> 00:54:09.227
Or how-- because people usually
write the way they speak.

00:54:09.227 --> 00:54:11.560
And usually the way you speak
is not necessarily the way

00:54:11.560 --> 00:54:12.530
you should be.

00:54:12.530 --> 00:54:15.320
So those are the corrections
that we usually do.

00:54:15.320 --> 00:54:17.810
And people understand them,
because most of the time

00:54:17.810 --> 00:54:19.660
it makes sense.

00:54:19.660 --> 00:54:22.370
I don't know if
anybody has questions.

00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:25.770
So let's see, next slides.

00:54:25.770 --> 00:54:29.190
So the other thing that
been happening in Africa

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:32.730
right now is a lot of people
have noticed the limitations

00:54:32.730 --> 00:54:36.720
of teaching people in
English, French, or Arabic,

00:54:36.720 --> 00:54:40.020
because like I said earlier,
if you go to your house,

00:54:40.020 --> 00:54:41.130
you speak in Pular.

00:54:41.130 --> 00:54:43.200
You go to the market,
you speak Pular.

00:54:43.200 --> 00:54:44.910
But the only time
you hear French

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:46.454
is when you go to school.

00:54:46.454 --> 00:54:48.120
Or the only time you
will start learning

00:54:48.120 --> 00:54:51.330
French is actually the first
day you sent to school.

00:54:51.330 --> 00:54:52.890
That created a
lot of limitation,

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:56.640
and policymakers have
been looking into ways

00:54:56.640 --> 00:55:01.650
to bring in our local languages,
at least as a way of teaching

00:55:01.650 --> 00:55:03.780
kids in primary school.

00:55:03.780 --> 00:55:07.020
There have been some pilot
programs being done either

00:55:07.020 --> 00:55:08.490
in Senegal or Cameroon.

00:55:08.490 --> 00:55:11.830
And eventually, what that
means with [INAUDIBLE] ECOWAS

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:14.970
and the African Union already
choosing certain languages--

00:55:14.970 --> 00:55:17.700
transnational languages--
is that one day,

00:55:17.700 --> 00:55:22.140
Fulani will be spoken
not just by the Fulanis,

00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:24.942
but by more people in
West Africa, for example.

00:55:24.942 --> 00:55:27.150
So right now if there are
50 million speaking Fulani,

00:55:27.150 --> 00:55:30.510
eventually there could be 100
or more than 150 million people

00:55:30.510 --> 00:55:31.069
speaking.

00:55:31.069 --> 00:55:32.610
Because the language
will be adopted.

00:55:32.610 --> 00:55:34.910
And the language is the
language of the community.

00:55:34.910 --> 00:55:36.730
The people, we know each other.

00:55:36.730 --> 00:55:40.862
So it would be easier to teach
somebody in Pular or Fulfulde,

00:55:40.862 --> 00:55:43.070
than to teach someone in
English, which is a language

00:55:43.070 --> 00:55:44.740
that he's not familiar with.

00:55:44.740 --> 00:55:47.910
So maybe, instead of
doing instruction,

00:55:47.910 --> 00:55:50.850
learning in French, we
will actually learn French.

00:55:50.850 --> 00:55:54.990
But we'll do the learning
in Fulfulde, or Mandingo,

00:55:54.990 --> 00:55:56.940
or Hausa, for example.

00:55:56.940 --> 00:56:02.407
So also, the other thing
that's the great with ADLaM

00:56:02.407 --> 00:56:04.490
is that since ADLaM is
spreading a lot in Nigeroa,

00:56:04.490 --> 00:56:06.210
we have a huge Fulani community.

00:56:06.210 --> 00:56:07.360
The Hausas are also--

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:10.440
some Hausas are
looking into adopting

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:13.980
the ADLaM alphabet to write
their own language also.

00:56:13.980 --> 00:56:19.050
And the director of the African
Languages program at Harvard

00:56:19.050 --> 00:56:20.840
has also expressed
interest in using

00:56:20.840 --> 00:56:22.710
ADLaM to write the
Swahili language,

00:56:22.710 --> 00:56:25.320
because he learned that
Swahili and Fulfulde are

00:56:25.320 --> 00:56:28.740
both non-tonal languages.

00:56:28.740 --> 00:56:31.470
Because he's already looking
into another script that's

00:56:31.470 --> 00:56:35.550
used in Africa for Kikuyu,
which is a tonal language.

00:56:35.550 --> 00:56:37.290
But Fulani is not
a tonal language,

00:56:37.290 --> 00:56:40.000
so he thinks that ADLaM will
be more appropriate for that.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:41.125
So he'll looking into that.

00:56:41.125 --> 00:56:43.650
And he'll be at the
conference in Conakry.

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:45.390
So there's also
a huge presence--

00:56:45.390 --> 00:56:47.800
if you go on Facebook,
you look up Fulani groups,

00:56:47.800 --> 00:56:49.470
you will see hundreds of them.

00:56:49.470 --> 00:56:52.050
We are very active
on social media.

00:56:52.050 --> 00:56:54.840
And many groups are promoting
not only ADLaM but all

00:56:54.840 --> 00:56:58.650
the aspects of the
Fulani culture.

00:56:58.650 --> 00:57:01.290
And there are many
movements supporting

00:57:01.290 --> 00:57:04.610
the ADLaM, especially
in Nigeria, in Guinea,

00:57:04.610 --> 00:57:05.850
and Cameroon.

00:57:05.850 --> 00:57:08.070
And so if you go
on social media--

00:57:08.070 --> 00:57:10.860
because Nigeria is the biggest
country in Africa, it's like,

00:57:10.860 --> 00:57:13.060
more than 180 million people--

00:57:13.060 --> 00:57:16.170
and if you get a list,
even 10% of those,

00:57:16.170 --> 00:57:19.237
to get involved in something,
you create a huge impact.

00:57:19.237 --> 00:57:20.820
And that's what's
happened with ADLaM,

00:57:20.820 --> 00:57:23.040
because since
Nigeria got involved,

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:24.460
it's gotten really big.

00:57:24.460 --> 00:57:29.970
Whether it's online
or on the ground.

00:57:29.970 --> 00:57:31.760
And so they've opened--

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:34.010
the way things are so big
there is that sometimes when

00:57:34.010 --> 00:57:37.115
they doing a graduation ADLaM,
they actually do at stadiums.

00:57:37.115 --> 00:57:39.240
Which is very different
from Guinea, because Guinea

00:57:39.240 --> 00:57:41.770
is a small country of
only 12 million people,

00:57:41.770 --> 00:57:44.410
compared to Nigeria, so.

00:57:44.410 --> 00:57:47.451
So this is where we stand today.

00:57:47.451 --> 00:57:50.380
I don't know if there's
anything else left.

00:57:50.380 --> 00:57:53.620
So yeah, these are
pictures of graduations.

00:57:53.620 --> 00:57:56.764
But we have so many
pictures, but we

00:57:56.764 --> 00:57:58.680
didn't want to turn the
presentation into just

00:57:58.680 --> 00:58:00.390
a slideshow of pictures.

00:58:00.390 --> 00:58:03.690
But if you go on Facebook,
you do a hashtag #adlam,

00:58:03.690 --> 00:58:06.846
you might see a lot of
stuff, or if you go online.

00:58:06.846 --> 00:58:08.220
We are actually
creating websites

00:58:08.220 --> 00:58:09.870
where we will collect
all of this stuff

00:58:09.870 --> 00:58:13.020
and put it there, for people to
know what's going on on ADLaM

00:58:13.020 --> 00:58:13.860
today.

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:17.220
So thank you all for listening,
and thank you for coming.

00:58:17.220 --> 00:58:19.740
And if you guys have any
questions, we'll feel free.

00:58:19.740 --> 00:58:22.270
We actually wanted to do only
30 minutes presentation and 30

00:58:22.270 --> 00:58:25.050
minute questions, but so
many things we talk about.

00:58:25.050 --> 00:58:27.090
But yeah, thank you so much.

00:58:27.090 --> 00:58:27.600
Thank you.

00:58:31.744 --> 00:58:33.660
SPEAKER: So you'll be
happy to take questions?

00:58:33.660 --> 00:58:34.540
ABDOULAYE BARRY: Yeah.

00:58:34.540 --> 00:58:36.956
AUDIENCE: And my question was
about sorting your alphabet.

00:58:36.956 --> 00:58:40.290
So when you made your alphabet,
how did you decide how you

00:58:40.290 --> 00:58:42.760
so-- like in Arabic, you
have [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:58:42.760 --> 00:58:45.349
but you went with
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:58:45.349 --> 00:58:47.140
ABDOULAYE BARRY:
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH], yes.

00:58:47.140 --> 00:58:49.269
AUDIENCE: How did
you decide that?

00:58:49.269 --> 00:58:51.060
ABDOULAYE BARRY: I
think the most obvious--

00:58:51.060 --> 00:58:54.490
it was the way we came
up with the letters.

00:58:54.490 --> 00:58:58.360
So sometimes we would
just make signs,

00:58:58.360 --> 00:59:01.230
and then when we'd pick a
letter from those signs,

00:59:01.230 --> 00:59:02.850
we will call the--

00:59:02.850 --> 00:59:04.870
we'll decide to
call [INAUDIBLE]--

00:59:04.870 --> 00:59:05.920
give it a name.

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:08.230
And that's how we actually
organized the alphabet.

00:59:08.230 --> 00:59:10.480
Or if I think of a letter--

00:59:10.480 --> 00:59:11.710
for example, I had a friend.

00:59:11.710 --> 00:59:13.960
When I would go to class, I
would start writing things

00:59:13.960 --> 00:59:14.920
to share with him.

00:59:14.920 --> 00:59:17.980
And then if I start writing
something and I'm blocked,

00:59:17.980 --> 00:59:20.620
stopped somewhere, because
I don't have that letter,

00:59:20.620 --> 00:59:23.710
so that day if I go home, that's
the letter I'll be creating.

00:59:23.710 --> 00:59:25.720
So then I'll add it to the list.

00:59:25.720 --> 00:59:27.860
And that's how we
completed the list.

00:59:27.860 --> 00:59:31.270
And we never really--

00:59:31.270 --> 00:59:33.025
after we completed
the set, the 27,

00:59:33.025 --> 00:59:36.580
we really never went back
and changed the order.

00:59:36.580 --> 00:59:40.082
So basically we made the list
as we created the letters.

00:59:40.082 --> 00:59:42.540
But we already knew we wanted
to-- the [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:59:42.540 --> 00:59:44.950
wanted to be the first
letter we created, of course,

00:59:44.950 --> 00:59:47.170
because it was the first
letter of my name anyway,

00:59:47.170 --> 00:59:51.400
so I wanted it to
be the first letter.

00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:54.337
And it's the first letter in
every other alphabet, almost.

00:59:54.337 --> 00:59:56.170
AUDIENCE: I have kind
of a related question.

00:59:56.170 --> 00:59:59.260
I was kind of struck by
how much attention there

00:59:59.260 --> 01:00:00.940
was to the aesthetics of it.

01:00:00.940 --> 01:00:03.550
Like, you started out with
this sort of automatic writing

01:00:03.550 --> 01:00:06.296
and visualization, and
then you talked about some

01:00:06.296 --> 01:00:08.170
of these decisions,
like, do we join letters?

01:00:08.170 --> 01:00:09.580
Or do we split them up?

01:00:09.580 --> 01:00:11.710
And then you go into
these calligraphy classes

01:00:11.710 --> 01:00:13.300
to really kind of polish it.

01:00:13.300 --> 01:00:17.200
So I guess I'd just
like to know what--

01:00:17.200 --> 01:00:20.500
anything you want to say about
that attention-- real attention

01:00:20.500 --> 01:00:22.750
to appearance?

01:00:22.750 --> 01:00:24.550
What your overall
strategy is, how

01:00:24.550 --> 01:00:27.370
you think that maybe
has been beneficial

01:00:27.370 --> 01:00:30.190
for adoption and
reception of the language?

01:00:30.190 --> 01:00:33.490
I mean, clearly ADLaM is
successful, and as you've said,

01:00:33.490 --> 01:00:35.379
there have been other
efforts to do this.

01:00:35.379 --> 01:00:37.420
So I'm wondering if the
aesthetic attention there

01:00:37.420 --> 01:00:39.010
is part of that.

01:00:39.010 --> 01:00:42.160
ABDOULAYE BARRY: Yes,
it has always been.

01:00:42.160 --> 01:00:45.130
When we first created
the alphabet, the more we

01:00:45.130 --> 01:00:48.190
wrote books, the
more we realized

01:00:48.190 --> 01:00:49.690
we can refine the letters.

01:00:49.690 --> 01:00:51.220
And that's how you
saw the evolution

01:00:51.220 --> 01:00:53.950
from how we were writing all
of them joined and then we

01:00:53.950 --> 01:00:55.720
went to unjoined letters.

01:00:55.720 --> 01:01:01.150
And also what do we notices
is, the better the letters look

01:01:01.150 --> 01:01:06.460
to people, the more interested
they are to the alphabet.

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:11.290
Because the colonization
has had a huge impact on us,

01:01:11.290 --> 01:01:14.680
and sometimes it's
hard for us to look

01:01:14.680 --> 01:01:18.580
into things that come from our
own culture as very valuable.

01:01:18.580 --> 01:01:22.180
Because basically, for
colonization to succeed,

01:01:22.180 --> 01:01:24.760
you have to basically
make people think

01:01:24.760 --> 01:01:26.950
that they're not that valuable.

01:01:26.950 --> 01:01:28.930
They have to take
everything from you--

01:01:28.930 --> 01:01:31.630
the language, the culture.

01:01:31.630 --> 01:01:36.190
So that mentality still
exists in our community.

01:01:36.190 --> 01:01:38.080
So aesthetics a
lot of part of it.

01:01:38.080 --> 01:01:44.572
And like my brother said, when
we created the first keyboard,

01:01:44.572 --> 01:01:46.030
and then we started
typing with it,

01:01:46.030 --> 01:01:49.420
he realized that it didn't
look as good as he wanted.

01:01:49.420 --> 01:01:51.910
And that's how he got
interested into calligraphy.

01:01:51.910 --> 01:01:54.080
And he's been making
amazing stuff with it.

01:01:54.080 --> 01:01:56.890
And it looks--
some of it looks--

01:01:56.890 --> 01:02:01.230
way, if you took what
we wrote in 1990,

01:02:01.230 --> 01:02:03.320
you compare it to
what's coming out today,

01:02:03.320 --> 01:02:05.445
from some of the stuff
that he's developing,

01:02:05.445 --> 01:02:06.721
it looks very different.

01:02:06.721 --> 01:02:07.720
And it looks way better.

01:02:07.720 --> 01:02:10.060
And yeah, aesthetics is--

01:02:10.060 --> 01:02:12.620
especially in our culture, if
you go on YouTube, actually.

01:02:12.620 --> 01:02:19.000
Go look up the Wodaabe, you'll
see how Wodaabe people--

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:23.210
W-O-D-A-A-B-E-- look
that up on YouTube,

01:02:23.210 --> 01:02:26.050
and you'll see how beauty is
important in Fulani culture.

01:02:26.050 --> 01:02:27.640
And so--

01:02:27.640 --> 01:02:30.910
AUDIENCE: I was wondering what
you do about other symbols,

01:02:30.910 --> 01:02:32.140
like punctuation?

01:02:32.140 --> 01:02:37.150
Do you have commas,
dashes, parentheses, stuff

01:02:37.150 --> 01:02:38.950
like that in your system?

01:02:38.950 --> 01:02:44.020
Or do you have regular
Latin or Arabic punctuation?

01:02:44.020 --> 01:02:45.700
ABDOULAYE BARRY: So
since the writing

01:02:45.700 --> 01:02:48.430
goes from right to
left, we use many

01:02:48.430 --> 01:02:50.470
of the Arabic punctuations.

01:02:50.470 --> 01:02:52.750
And we do have some
different ones,

01:02:52.750 --> 01:02:56.020
because the Fulani language is--

01:02:56.020 --> 01:02:58.510
so my brother is actually the
one who came up with that--

01:02:58.510 --> 01:03:00.730
when we are talking,
sometimes you'll

01:03:00.730 --> 01:03:02.860
say an affirmative sentence.

01:03:02.860 --> 01:03:05.050
If it's written--
it's not a question.

01:03:05.050 --> 01:03:08.470
But it's only a question
by how it sounds.

01:03:08.470 --> 01:03:10.900
So that's how we came up
with different symbols

01:03:10.900 --> 01:03:12.970
to indicate whether a
sentence is actually

01:03:12.970 --> 01:03:15.610
a question before
you start reading it,

01:03:15.610 --> 01:03:19.576
so you know how to
change your tone.

01:03:19.576 --> 01:03:21.950
AUDIENCE: OK, so that's also
part of your writing system,

01:03:21.950 --> 01:03:24.350
is some of this
additional punctuation.

01:03:24.350 --> 01:03:25.420
Thank you.

01:03:25.420 --> 01:03:29.410
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
how you typically represent

01:03:29.410 --> 01:03:32.080
numbers in the script?

01:03:32.080 --> 01:03:39.360
Do you use the Latin digits,
ASCII digits one, two, three,

01:03:39.360 --> 01:03:42.230
do you use Arabic, or do
you have your own digits?

01:03:42.230 --> 01:03:46.090
And do you usually use a
base 10 numbering system?

01:03:46.090 --> 01:03:49.090
Or do you use something else?

01:03:49.090 --> 01:03:52.440
ABDOULAYE BARRY: So we
have our own set of digits,

01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:56.620
the 10 digits from 1 to 0.

01:03:56.620 --> 01:03:59.320
We don't use the
Latin or the Arabic,

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:02.530
because basically
the problem also

01:04:02.530 --> 01:04:06.165
is, since the writing system
goes from right to left,

01:04:06.165 --> 01:04:10.550
and the way we read numbers
is also from right to left.

01:04:10.550 --> 01:04:15.250
So we created, also, digits
to represent numbers that also

01:04:15.250 --> 01:04:17.210
go from right to left as well.

01:04:17.210 --> 01:04:20.580
So if we're writing 1996,
for example, it would go--

01:04:20.580 --> 01:04:25.450
if somebody is reading--
it would be like 6991,

01:04:25.450 --> 01:04:28.990
if it's in Latin or Arabic.

01:04:28.990 --> 01:04:33.160
So we have our
own set of digits.

01:04:33.160 --> 01:04:36.730
And also the thing with
ADLaM is that since people

01:04:36.730 --> 01:04:39.770
view it as original-- when
we first created this,

01:04:39.770 --> 01:04:41.840
it was just a way
for us to maybe solve

01:04:41.840 --> 01:04:44.720
a problem of standardization.

01:04:44.720 --> 01:04:49.240
By now, it has become something
bigger, as a way actually

01:04:49.240 --> 01:04:50.710
to educate more people.

01:04:50.710 --> 01:04:53.350
Because like my brother say,
we have a huge percentage

01:04:53.350 --> 01:04:56.530
of people that don't
go to school in Guinea.

01:04:56.530 --> 01:04:58.750
Or everywhere in Africa.

01:04:58.750 --> 01:05:03.660
But that's because education
is not done in our languages,

01:05:03.660 --> 01:05:05.194
it's done in foreign languages.

01:05:05.194 --> 01:05:06.610
So basically if
you don't know how

01:05:06.610 --> 01:05:08.334
to speak French, or
English, or Arabic,

01:05:08.334 --> 01:05:10.000
you are considered
an illiterate person.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.820
So a newspaper-- you will
not have access to it.

01:05:12.820 --> 01:05:14.590
Or information
given on the radio--

01:05:14.590 --> 01:05:17.270
you will not have
access to that as well.

01:05:17.270 --> 01:05:19.390
And one of the most
amazing things that--

01:05:19.390 --> 01:05:21.040
or the most fulfilling
thing for me

01:05:21.040 --> 01:05:26.610
is, when my mom came here to
visit a few years ago, in 2012,

01:05:26.610 --> 01:05:31.420
and this area is very
different from Africa.

01:05:31.420 --> 01:05:33.770
In Africa we live in
communities where everybody

01:05:33.770 --> 01:05:36.250
is outside, but here what
was very different for her

01:05:36.250 --> 01:05:38.230
is the fact that
everyone lives inside.

01:05:38.230 --> 01:05:40.810
When you go in your
house, you lock your door.

01:05:40.810 --> 01:05:42.700
And you don't-- you know.

01:05:42.700 --> 01:05:43.870
So it was very hard for her.

01:05:43.870 --> 01:05:46.770
So if we go to work, she would
spend all her day at home,

01:05:46.770 --> 01:05:47.980
not have anything to do.

01:05:47.980 --> 01:05:49.660
So the only way for
her-- she's never

01:05:49.660 --> 01:05:51.490
been to a French school
or English school.

01:05:51.490 --> 01:05:54.220
So she doesn't know how to read
or write in English or French.

01:05:54.220 --> 01:05:56.650
So the only way she can
pass her time all day

01:05:56.650 --> 01:06:00.480
was reading the
ADLaM newspapers.

01:06:00.480 --> 01:06:01.450
And one day she said--

01:06:01.450 --> 01:06:01.750
IBRAHIM BARRY: And books.

01:06:01.750 --> 01:06:03.125
ABDOULAYE BARRY:
Yeah, and books.

01:06:03.125 --> 01:06:06.460
And she said she did not
realize how lost she was.

01:06:06.460 --> 01:06:08.231
Because now she can
read the newspaper

01:06:08.231 --> 01:06:09.980
and know what's going
on around the world.

01:06:09.980 --> 01:06:13.570
And that was really amazing
for me, it had a huge impact.

01:06:13.570 --> 01:06:16.370
Like, even if it was
just left to this,

01:06:16.370 --> 01:06:18.880
if this was where it
was actually with ADLaM,

01:06:18.880 --> 01:06:20.420
I'm satisfied.

01:06:20.420 --> 01:06:23.890
AUDIENCE: One of my models
for success in a language

01:06:23.890 --> 01:06:27.890
is that people are able to
use it for everyday things.

01:06:27.890 --> 01:06:30.530
And texting is one
of those things.

01:06:30.530 --> 01:06:33.340
If ADLaM were available
on mobile devices,

01:06:33.340 --> 01:06:35.841
would young people be
texting their friends,

01:06:35.841 --> 01:06:37.840
lying to their parents
about where they're going

01:06:37.840 --> 01:06:39.190
after school, things like that?

01:06:41.810 --> 01:06:44.350
ABDOULAYE BARRY:
Yes, absolutely.

01:06:44.350 --> 01:06:49.030
Because like I said, people want
to use so bad, sp even to text,

01:06:49.030 --> 01:06:52.720
they'll just write it
on a piece of paper

01:06:52.720 --> 01:06:54.910
and take a picture
of that and send it.

01:06:54.910 --> 01:06:57.010
Just because they
want to text in ADLaM.

01:06:57.010 --> 01:07:00.400
And like I-- also
we said, most people

01:07:00.400 --> 01:07:04.030
don't go to French
or English school.

01:07:04.030 --> 01:07:06.640
So it's easier for them to just
text in their own language.

01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:09.670
And if ADLaM is
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

01:07:09.670 --> 01:07:11.850
And it's also, people feel
more comfortable writing

01:07:11.850 --> 01:07:14.510
in Fulfulde using ADLaM
than actually writing

01:07:14.510 --> 01:07:15.970
it using another alphabet.

01:07:15.970 --> 01:07:18.290
Because if somebody texts
you or writes something,

01:07:18.290 --> 01:07:22.300
make a comment on Facebook,
in Pular or Fulfulde using

01:07:22.300 --> 01:07:24.960
the Latin script, it's an
exercise to actually figure out

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:25.870
what's written there.

01:07:25.870 --> 01:07:28.900
Because nobody goes to school.

01:07:28.900 --> 01:07:30.580
Most people don't go
to school and learn

01:07:30.580 --> 01:07:34.750
how to write in Pular
using the Latin alphabet.

01:07:34.750 --> 01:07:39.820
And since, as that question
about phonetic sense,

01:07:39.820 --> 01:07:41.410
ADLaM is very phonetic.

01:07:41.410 --> 01:07:43.890
So the way you read it is
the way-- or the way you say

01:07:43.890 --> 01:07:45.010
is the way you write.

01:07:45.010 --> 01:07:50.140
So the chance of
mistakes is very slim.

01:07:50.140 --> 01:07:54.750
IBRAHIM BARRY: And like
I said at the beginning,

01:07:54.750 --> 01:07:57.790
smartphone are everywhere,
but the only thing people

01:07:57.790 --> 01:08:02.090
do with their smartphone is
just calling and receiving.

01:08:02.090 --> 01:08:07.090
And now they know they can read
and write in their language,

01:08:07.090 --> 01:08:09.730
but they cannot do
the other functions.

01:08:09.730 --> 01:08:12.010
They cannot write
the name and save.

01:08:12.010 --> 01:08:13.660
The most of the time--

01:08:13.660 --> 01:08:17.290
most of the people I meet
who didn't go to school,

01:08:17.290 --> 01:08:22.330
they just memorize numbers of
the people they really know.

01:08:22.330 --> 01:08:24.100
They don't save names.

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:27.310
Or they have is
notebook they write.

01:08:27.310 --> 01:08:32.410
But if ADLaM is in their system,
they can write their name.

01:08:32.410 --> 01:08:34.710
Save their schedules.

01:08:34.710 --> 01:08:35.855
It's going to be amazing.

01:08:35.855 --> 01:08:37.355
ABDOULAYE BARRY:
And the other thing

01:08:37.355 --> 01:08:39.279
is also the economics of it.

01:08:39.279 --> 01:08:42.109
Because it's cheaper
to text than to call.

01:08:42.109 --> 01:08:45.310
So people prefer to
send text messages.

01:08:45.310 --> 01:08:47.200
And like I said, we
are nomadic people.

01:08:47.200 --> 01:08:50.170
And even though we don't
follow cattles everywhere now,

01:08:50.170 --> 01:08:51.956
but it's basically in our blood.

01:08:51.956 --> 01:08:53.080
Fulani people travel light.

01:08:53.080 --> 01:08:55.810
It's very rare to see
a Fulani person who's

01:08:55.810 --> 01:08:58.420
living in the region
where he was born.

01:08:58.420 --> 01:09:01.240
And for that reason, people
are always communicating.

01:09:01.240 --> 01:09:03.520
Figuring out ways to
communicate with each other.

01:09:03.520 --> 01:09:07.870
And texting is one of the most
amazing ways people can text.

01:09:07.870 --> 01:09:10.580
So there are Fulanis
everywhere in the world.

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:12.460
So you can go to a
city, big city where

01:09:12.460 --> 01:09:13.590
you will not find a Fulani.

01:09:13.590 --> 01:09:16.569
And there's actually a saying
in our culture, or in Africa--

01:09:16.569 --> 01:09:19.600
if you go to a place and you
see no Fulani there, move.

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:21.100
Because that place is not good.

01:09:21.100 --> 01:09:23.800
IBRAHIM BARRY: The other tribes
say that, like the Mandingo.

01:09:23.800 --> 01:09:25.300
ABDOULAYE BARRY:
So we travel a lot.

01:09:25.300 --> 01:09:28.779
And we need to communi-- we
need to stay in con-- because we

01:09:28.779 --> 01:09:30.229
were the only few
people also that

01:09:30.229 --> 01:09:33.160
use-- it was part of our
culture to write letters

01:09:33.160 --> 01:09:35.170
and go to the market
or to your park

01:09:35.170 --> 01:09:37.300
and give it to some
random person and say,

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:41.590
I have one of my relatives that
live in the city called Lola,

01:09:41.590 --> 01:09:43.523
and I don't know
exactly where he lives.

01:09:43.523 --> 01:09:45.939
So I give him the letter and
then the person would take it

01:09:45.939 --> 01:09:49.899
and then go looking for certain
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] from

01:09:49.899 --> 01:09:52.660
[INAUDIBLE] until they find
him and give him the letter.

01:09:52.660 --> 01:09:55.660
And then he will take the letter
to somebody who will read it.

01:09:55.660 --> 01:09:56.780
So yeah, communication.

01:09:56.780 --> 01:09:57.310
Texting.

01:09:57.310 --> 01:10:02.530
If we were able to text, that
would makes a huge difference

01:10:02.530 --> 01:10:04.660
for ADLaM and for the people.

